07283nam a22008415i 9780824840174DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248401747 a10.1515/97808248401742doi  a(DE-B1597)484394  a(OCoLC)881137479  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aSOC0430002bisacsh04a275/.08222300aEncountering Modernity :bChristianity in East Asia and Asian America /ced. by David K. Yoo, Albert L. Park, Russell Leong. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b7 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIntersections: Asian and Pacific American Transcultural Studies ;v4100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Modernity and the Materiality of Religion -- tPart I. Economy and Religion -- t1. A Sacred Economy of Value and Production Capitalism and Protestantism in Early Modern Korea (1885–1919) -- t2. Taking Jesus Public The Neoliberal Transformation of Korean Megachurches -- tPart II. Religion and Social Relations -- t3. Guanxi and Gospel Mapping Christian Networks in South China -- t4. Accidental Pilgrims Modernity, Migration, and Christian Conversion among Contemporary Taiwanese Americans -- tPart III. The Sacred and Social Activism -- t5. Christianity and Civil Society in Colonial Korea The Civil Society Movement of Cho Man-sik and the P’yŏngyang YMCA against Japanese Colonialism -- t6. Between Mission and Medicine The Early History of Severance Hospital -- t7. Kagawa Toyohiko (1888–1960) and the Japanese Christian Impact on American Society -- tPart IV. Religion and National Identity -- t8. Preaching Modern Japan National Imaginaries and Protestant Sermons in Meiji and Taishō Tokyo -- t9. “Smelling of Pickled Radish, Not Butter” The Wartime Search for a Christianity Viable in Japan -- t10. Diasporic Korean Christianity in the United States, 1922–1941 -- t11. Protestant Christianity in Reform-Era China Realities and Representations -- tSelected Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe story of Catholicism and Protestantism in China, Japan, and Korea has been told in great detail. The existing literature is especially rich in documenting church and missionary activities as well as how varied regions and cultures have translated Christian ideas and practices. Less evident, however, are studies that contextualize Christianity within the larger economic, political, social, and cultural developments in each of the three countries and its diasporas. The contributors to Encountering Modernity address such concerns and collectively provide insights into Christianity’s role in the development of East Asia and as it took shape among East Asians in the United States.The work brings together studies of Christianity in China, Taiwan, Korea, and Japan and its diasporas to expand the field through new angles of vision and interpretation. Its mode of analysis not only results in a deeper understanding of Christianity, but also produces more informed and nuanced histories of East Asian countries that take seriously the structures and sensibilities of religion—broadly understood and within a national and transnational context. It critically investigates how Protestant Christianity was negotiated and interpreted by individuals in Korea, China (with a brief look at Taiwan), and Japan starting in the nineteenth century as all three countries became incorporated into the global economy and the international nation-state system anchored by the West. People in East Asia from various walks of life studied and, in some cases, embraced principles of Christianity as a way to frame and make meaningful the economic, political, and social changes they experienced because of modernity. Encountering Modernity makes a significant contribution by moving beyond issues of missiology and church history to ask how Christianity represented an encounter with modernity that set into motion tremendous changes throughout East Asia and in transnational diasporic communities in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh1 aChang, Kyusik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEasley, Eun Young Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Joseph Tse-Hei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeong, Russell, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMullins, Mark R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOwnby, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPark, Albert L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPark, Albert L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPark, Yunjae, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVanderbilt, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWashington, Garrett L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoo, David K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoo, David K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082484017440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824840174423Coveruhttps:/